Remarriage of widows seems to have been permitted in the ancient days ç
under certain conditions. Such a woman was known as `punarbh<220>'.
A punarbh<220> was of three kinds:
1. A maiden whose marriage was not consummated and whose husband died ç
suddenly. 2. A woman accused of adultery but returned to her parents ç
who gave her in marriage to another man. 3. A widow remarried to a ç
close relative of her husband. (Whether she was childless or not, ç
is not clear in this case.)
A married woman was permitted to remarry by some dharma·<193>stras ç
under the following conditions:
When a husband dies very early or is lost or unheard of for a long ç
time; if he becomes a sa<221>ny<193>sin (monk); if he isimpotent ç
or suffering from incurable diseases or a sinner.
Though remarriage was perhaps permitted in the earliest age (vide ç
<184>gveda 10.18.7 and 8; Atharvaveda 5.17.8 and 9), during the ç
later period, more stringent rules were imposed for the same. Some ç
of the sm<216>tis even frowned upon the custom (vide Manusm<216>ti ç
9.47; 8.226). Insistence on chastity and the social implications like ç
maidens not getting good husbands may be one of the reasons for the ç
hardening of this stand.
