@SPACE1 = 
The Vedas are the basic scriptures of Hinduism. However, modern Hindu ç
religious practices, as they obtain today, are deeply indebted to ç
the pur<193><207>as. Whether it is meditation on God the Absolute, ç
or the queer modes of worship of a grotesque idol of a village deity, ç
everyone of the religious practices of Hinduism finds an honourable ç
place in the pur<193><207>as. This is because they have recognized ç
the need for a variety of approaches to God, to suit the bewildering ç
divergence of human temperaments. If the Hindu society has not been ç
swept off its feet by the incessant invasions of barbarians or the ç
powerful impacts of semitic religions or even the periodic internal ç
upheavals by heretics, it is not a little due to the pur<193><207>as. ç
They have not only prevented it from disintegrating, but, on the other ç
hand, have strengthened it immensely by imparting it a tenacious resilience, ç
rarely seen in human history. This, they have done, not by adopting ç
a tough and dogmatic approach, but bymaking various internal adjustments, ç
keeping however, the core of the religion intact.
There is an additional reason as to why the pur<193><207>as have become ç
the saviours of Hinduism. It is because they have encompassed all ç
aspects of human life, whether sacred or secular. This has naturally ç
made them grow to encyclopaedic proportions. At a time when the only ç
access to knowledge for the common masses was by listening to the ç
pur<193><207>as, they have discharged their duties to the society ç
admirably well.
@SB8.5 = Antiquity of the Pur<193><207>as
The  word  `pur<193><207>a'  is  generally derived  in  two  ways:  pur<193>  bhava<221> ç
(`ancient narratives') and pur<193> api navam (`that which was new ç
even in the ancient days'). Hence, the pur<193><207>as can be defined ç
as narratives belonging to the ancient period, and yet, containing ç
materials relevant to all ages, and so, `ever new and fresh'. Actually, ç
the pur<193><207>as are of great antiquity. The word `pur<193><207>a'†sometimes ç
in association with the word `itih<193>sa' (epic)†occurs in other ç
ancient works like the Atharvaveda and the <185>atapatha Br<193>hma<207>a ç
as also in some older Upani<218>ads like the B<216>had<193>ra<207>yaka ç
and the Ch<193>ndogya. Attributing the origin of the pur<193><207>as ç
to Mah<193>bh<220>ta (`the Great Being' or God) or to Brahm<193> (the ç
Creator), and their close association with the Vedic sacrifices as ç
`akhy<193>nabh<193>ga' or narrative portion leads us to believe that ç
they are as old as the Vedas, or perhaps, older still. This is corroborated ç
by the fact that the kings Divod<193>sa, Sud<193>sa, Somaka and others ç
known to the <184>gveda have been placed very low in the genealogical ç
lists given in the pur<193><207>as. Of course, by the word `pur<193><207>a,' ç
the extant class of literature known to us as the pur<193><207>as, ç
is not meant, but only ancient stories and legends. They are often ç
indicated by the words `pur<193><207>a' or `pur<193><207>asa<221>hit<193>'.
@SB8.5 = General Characteristics of the Pur<193><207>as
A pur<193><207>a is defined as a work having five characteristics ç
describing: sarga (creation), pratisarga (intermediate creation), ç
va<221>·a (dynasties of gods and of the patriarchs),  manvantara  (the  fourteen ç
Manus and their periods) and va<221>·<193>nucarita (genealogy of the ç
kings of the solar and the lunar race). Sometimes a few more are added ç
such asrak<218><193> (protection of the world by theavat<193>ras ç
or incarnations), sa<221>sth<193> (pralaya or dissolution of the world), ç
hetu (the cause of creation viz., the j<200>va and its karma), v<216>tti ç
(modes of subsistence) and ap<193>·raya (the refuge or Brahman).
Except the Vi<218><207>upur<193><207>a, none of the others exhibits ç
all the five characteristics. On the other hand, many other subjects ç
like ·r<193>ddha (obsequial rites), duties of the var<207>as and the ç
<193>·ramas, d<193>nas (gifts), t<200>rthas (places of pilgrimage), ç
and images and their worship find a prominent place in the pur<193><207>as. ç
Quite a few pur<193><207>as contain a lot of material aimed at the ç
propagation of a particular cult (e.g., <185>aivism or Vai<218><207>avism). ç
A lot of information regarding other areas†mostly secular †of knowledge ç
like °yurveda (the science of health), architecture and town-planning, ç
prognostication through omens and astro-logy is also found in the ç
pur<193><207>as since they were the sole means of educating the masses ç
during those days.
@SB8.5 = Evolution of the Pur<193><207>as
Though it is conceded that the pur<193><207>as are of hoary antiquity, ç
extreme paucity of information leaves us in complete darkness with ç
regard to their character or contents, none of which seems to have ç
come down to us in the original form. No doubt Hindu tradition attributes ç
the authorship of these pur<193><207>as†the eighteen Mah<193>pur<193><207>as ç
(the main pur<193><207>as) and the eighteen Upapur<193><207>as (the ç
subsidiary pur<193><207>as)†to the sage K<216><218><207>a Dvaip<193>yana, ç
better known as Vedavy<193>sa or Vy<193>sa. However, this cannot be ç
substantiated by the evidence available. The original pur<193><207>a ç
referred to in the Vedic and allied literature was, perhaps, a conglomeration ç
of <193>khy<193>nas (tales), up<193>khy<193>nas (anecdotes), g<193>th<193>s ç
(metrical songs or proverbial sayings current in the ancient society) ç
and Kalpako<219>is (sayings that had come down through the ages). ç
The sage Vedavy<193>sa might have compiled these into one Pur<193><207>asa<221>hit<193>. ç
His disciples and their disciples as also others in that tradition ç
might have composed more detailed works which gradually took the present ç
form, the eighteen pur<193><207>as as we know them today. This surmise ç
is confirmed by the accounts given in some of the more ancient pur<193><207>as ç
like the V<193>yupur<193><207>a, the Brahm<193><207><195>apur<193><207>a ç
and the Vi<218><207>upur<193><207>a. According to them, after compiling ç
the original Pur<193><207>asa<221>hit<193>, Vy<193>sa imparted it ç
to his disciple S<220>ta Romahar<218>a<207>a (also spelt as Lomahar<218>a<207>a), ç
who in his turn made it into six versions and taught them to his six ç
disciples. Of these, three disciples viz., K<193>·yapa, S<193>var<207>i ç
and <185><193><221>sap<193>yana made three separate sa<221>hit<193>s ç
which were named after them. These three, along with that of Romahar<218>a<207>a, ç
are known as `m<220>lasa<221>hit<193>s'. The later pur<193><207>as ç
were evolved out of these.
@SB8.5 = Growth of the Present Mah<193>pur<193><207>as
When exactly the original pur<193>nic material began to give rise ç
to different pur<193><207>asa<221>hit<193>s, it is difficult to say. ç
Since the Taittir<200>ya °ra<207>yaka as also the law-books of Manu ç
and Y<193>j<210>avalkya have used the word `pur<193><207><193>ni' ç
(the `pur<193><207>as,' in plural number) it cannot be denied that ç
three or more pur<193><207>as had come into existence long before ç
the beginning of the Christian era. By the time of °pastamba (450-350 ç
<MS>B.C.<D>) the term `pur<193><207>a' had already become restricted ç
to designate a particular class of books. It is not known how many ç
pur<193><207>as existed during °pastamba's time and how they went ç
on growing in number. But we do find a tradition recorded in almost ç
all the extant pur<193><207>as and other allied works, that the pur<193><207>as, ç
or rather the Mah<193>pur<193><207>as, are eighteen in number. The ç
names of these eighteen pur<193><207>as as given in different pur<193><207>ic ç
works, are more or less the same as those of the works now extant ç
under the general title `Mah<193>pur<193><207>a'. Based on the evidence ç
of the Matsya and the K<220>rma pur<193><207>as as also some other ç
Sanskrit works, we can safely assume that by <MS>A.D.<D> 700, the ç
evolution into eighteen Mah<193>-pur<193><207>as had become complete ç
and the number got rigidly fixed there.
