By far, the most well-known of all the pur<193><207>as, the Bh<193>gavata, ç
also called Sr<200>mad Bh<193>gavata, is considered as the most ç
authoritative text dealing with <185>r<200>k<216><218><207>a's life ç
and doings. The book, however, deals extensively with the stories ç
of other incarnations of Vi<218><207>u also. The work is in the form ç
of a narration by the young sage <185>uka (son of Vy<193>sa) to the ç
king Par<200>k<218>it, at his request to listen to the glories of ç
Lord K<216><218><207>a-V<193>sudeva. This pur<193><207>a deals with ç
the following topics: story of the king Par<200>k<218>it and the beginning ç
of the narration of the Bh<193>gavata; the cosmic form of God and ç
creation of the world; curse incurred by Jaya and Vijaya, the attendants ç
of Lord Vi<218><207>u as also the story of Hira<207>yaka·ipu and the ç
child-devotee Prahl<193>da; story of the great sage Kapila; story ç
of the destruction ofDak<218>a's sacrifice by Rudra; story of another ç
child-devotee Dhruva; story of Ja<195>abharata; the descent of the ç
river Ga<209>g<193> to the earth; the destruction of Tripura or the ç
three cities by <185>iva; the story of the churning of the ocean and ç
of V<193>mana.
