It is to be kept in mind that the paur<193><207>ic concept of time ç
is cyclic, based on the theory that creation, sustenance and destruction ç
(s<216><218><219>i, sthiti and pralaya) take place in a cyclic order, ç
having no specific beginning or end. Since modern history is based ç
on the linear concept of time, the historical traditions of the pur<193><207>as ç
may appear to be enigmatic.
Events themselves pass away with their occurrence. However, they survive ç
as memories registered in the psyche of the human beings and can stimulate ç
them for creative activities. A chain of such powerful stimulations ç
gets established as a tradition. The pur<193><207>as are repositories ç
of such traditions from the most ancient times. Their utility lies ç
in contributing to the continuity and betterment of the civilisation ç
and culture of a people. Hence, though they may not fit into the frame-work ç
of `history' as defined by the modern man, they cannot be dismissed ç
as fiction either! They were originally based on facts and hence can ç
