The pur<193><207>as recognize two types of dharmas: s<193>dh<193>ra<207>a ç
or s<193>m<193>nya dharma (generic) and vi·e<218>a dharma or svadharma ç
(specific).
The individual, being an integral part of the society owes a duty ç
to himself and to the society. Since his rise and fall affect the ç
society, he must endeavour to raise himself to the fullest stature.
Hence there is no conflict between the individual and the social duties.
Dharma contributes to the welfare and progress of the human society, ç
nay, of the whole world. In the puru<218><193>rtha scheme of life, ç
dharma occupies the first place. It is the best kith and kin of the ç
embodied soul not only in life, but also after death. It wanes from ç
its full strength in the K<216>tayuga to only a quarter in the Kaliyuga.
The  pur<193><207>as  have  successfully reconciled the s<193>dh<193>ra<207>a-dharmas ç
with svadharma. Whereas the former comprise virtues that impart refinement ç
and culture to an individual, the latter is a practical application ç
of the former within a particular sphere by an individual belonging ç
to a class characterised by certain prominent qualities or gu<207>as. ç
The scheme of var<207>a and <193>·rama dharmas which the pur<193><207>as ç
unanimously advocate, is based upon the duties of the individuals ç
of a class. It aims at material and spiritual perfection of the society ç
as a whole.
The s<193>dh<193>ra<207>a-dharmas are universal in scope and eternal ç
in nature. Though the pur<193><207>as enumerate them generally as ç
ten, a few more virtues are sometimes added, making the list longer. ç
They are: ahi<221>s<193> (non-injury), satya (truthfulness), k<218>am<193> ç
or k<218><193>nti (forbearance), dama or indriyanigraha (self control), ç
·ama (inner peace), day<193> (compassion), d<193>na (charity), ·auca ç
(purity), tapas (austerity) and j<210><193>na (wisdom).
Of these, satya and ahi<221>s<193> are extolled highly. <185>auca ç
(purity), both internal and external, is stressed as an indispensable ç
socio-ethical virtue. Tapas which includes disinterested action is ç
a must for achieving anything great in life. D<193>na is also eulogised ç
much as a social duty.
Coming  to  the  vi·e<218>a-dharmas (svadharma) or var<207><193>·rama-dharmas, ç
the pur<193><207>as deal with them extensively. The var<207>a system ç
represents a natural division of the society based on gu<207>a (nature) ç
and karma (vocation). The <193>·rama scheme of life helps an individual ç
to evolve himself from the stage of a novice in pursuit of learning ç
to the stage of a person ever living in God. Both these systems enjoin ç
