Other ideas that find a place in the pur<193><207>as are the theory ç
of karma and punarjanma (transmigration), pr<193>ya·cittas (expiations ç
for sins), vratas (religious observances) and t<200>rthay<193>tr<193> ç
(pilgrimage).
`As you sow, so you reap' is the principle behind the theory of karma. ç
Since actions always produce their corresponding results, human beings ç
are advised to eschew evil and always do good. Effect of sins committed, ç
knowingly or unknowingly, can be got rid of, or at least minimised, ç
by performing proper expiations prescribed for them.
Vratas or religious observances with their stress on fasting and self-control ç
help in self-purification. So also t<200>rthay<193>tr<193> or visiting ç
places of pilgrimage, associated with gods or saints.
@SB8.5 = Popular Religion in the Pur<193><207>as
The labyrinth of Vedic sacrifices on one side and the uncompromising ç
way of renunciation as taught by the Upani<218>adic sages on the other, ç
both of which were beyond the reach of the common masses, drove the ç
ordinary people, whose hunger for religion was no less sincere, into ç
the arms of Buddhism and Jainism. It was at this juncture that the ç
pur<193><207>as as we know them today, started evolving. The paths ç
of karma and bhakti, with their various ramifications were gradually ç
introduced into them. Over the centuries they have grown both in quantity ç
and in quality, so much so, that they are now the bed-rock of modern ç
Hinduism.
Temples and temple rituals, domestic worship along with the associated ç
religious rites, vratas (religious vows and festivals) and t<200>rthay<193>tr<193> ç
(pilgrimage) invariably find a prominent place in the pur<193><207>as. ç
Sometimes, details of construction of temples and their consecration ç
are also given.
Instructions regarding ritualistic worship, both independently and ç
as a part of the vratas, also find a place. They include aspects of ç
austerity associated with them such as fasting and keeping vigil.
Of the sixteen sa<221>sk<193>ras or sacraments, only ·r<193>ddha (obsequial ç
rites) has been given a pre-eminent place though the others also are ç
dealt with.
Bhakti or devotion to God (especially towards the well-known deities ç
of the Hindu pantheon, including the avat<193>ras or incarnations) ç
is another subject dealt with in great detail in the pur<193><207>as. ç
They extol the extraordinary powers of the mantras (divine names) ç
and have also given substantial information about the science of the ç
mantras (mantra·<193>stra). However, the general trend is always towards ç
stressing the unity of the Godheadand emphasising that the various ç
deities are only its aspects. Vilification of some deities and their ç
followers is an exception and may safely be brushed aside as an aberration ç
or as interpolations by fanatics.
@SB8.5 = Upapur<193><207>as
Though tradition fixed the number of the Mah<193>pur<193><207>as as ç
eighteen, the growth of pur<193><207>a literature went on unabated. ç
Hence those of the pur<193><207>as which did not or could not find ç
a place in that list were accommodated under the title `Upapur<193><207>as'. ç
In course of time the number ofthese Upapur<193><207>as also got ç
fixed at eighteen. They were considered as appendices to the Mah<193>pur<193><207>as ç
and hence of lesser importance. However, quite a few of them are large ç
enough in size and important enough in content, that they compel us ç
to treat them with respect. The number also has exceeded eighteen.
The lists of these Upapur<193><207>as, as given in the various Mah<193>pur<193><207>as ç
do not tally. Some of the pur<193><207>as listed under the Mah<193>pur<193><207>as, ç
as for instance, Brahm<193><207>da or V<193>mana, find a place ç
in the lists of Upapur<193><207>as also. Some of these Upapur<193><207>as ç
