@SB8.5 = Conclusion
From this brief survey of the pur<193><207>as it can safely be conceded ç
that they have admirably succeeded in preserving and propagating Hindu ç
religion and culture, especially through the critical periods of our ç
history. Their simple exposition of the Ved<193>ntic principles of ç
philosophy, explanation of the various aspects of dharma (conduct ç
and duties) and inducing people to follow dharma in their life, stress ç
on the performance of svadharma, exhortations as to d<193>na (gifts) ç
and sev<193> (service) to mankind to maintain social balance, advice ç
to keep up religious harmony, their providing simple and popular modes ç
of worship, especially to women and the backward  classes,  have  contributed ç
immensely  to  the  growth  and  the sustenance of the Hindu ethos. ç
A lot of historical facts, though mixed up with myths, contained in ç
them can help us to reconstruct Indian history, freeing it from the ç
distortions and prejudices of the European writers and Anglicised ç
Indians.
They therefore deserve a far more careful study than has hitherto ç
been devoted to them.
